title: Cassian Andor Headcanons:
body:
Cassian x Shy Reader Would Include:

  • him being really sweet
  • he first notices you during a mission briefing, despite you trying so hard to not be noticed
  • he would love how you would blush anytime he approached you
  • you being really reserved at first, but opened up little by little
  • every time you opened up, Cassian would fall in love with you more
  • him being the first to confess his feelings
  • you shyly admit yours
  • him being so swept up in the moment that he kisses you
  • it really shocks you at first, but you love the way his lips feel
  • definitely super protective of you
  • him understanding when you just want to have a date night in
  • when there is a huge crowd, you always search for him
  • he is never too far away, and wraps you up in his arms
  • just having an amazing relationship

{First of all, I am in love with Cassian. Rogue One is my top 3 Star Wars films! Requests are open, so please send them in! GIF is not mine, found on GIPHY}

body:
Ezra and Sabine’s reunion

I can’t draw at all. But I can imagine it. He has been stranded, but thriving. The purgill took him somewhere safe. He is black-bearded, broad-chested, feral, but hasn’t lost himself. He runs to her. She is exhausted from the journey but lights up. I guess it’s snowing? Or they’re in an ice cave? Cold planet. He’s been expecting her. His eyes match her hair. They embrace.

Anyway that’s how I would draw it, if I could.

tags: several years after anyone cares about this i still have thoughts
title: Random Thought
body:
Pre- and Post-Moffat era Doctor Who is a lot like Star Trek:  wildly variant episode quality from week to week and from writer to writer; cheap costumes, scenery, and special effects that require a lot of suspension of disbelief, but that fans eventually become fond of as one of the quirks of the show; shifts in tone so great it’s almost like getting a new genre every episode (is this one a sitcom or a whodunnit? Horror? Political drama? Exploration adventure?  (Space) Naval epic? Tune in to find out!); cerebral plots that still aren’t afraid of genuine emotion; mostly about well-intentioned but very different people trying to deal with danger and emergencies in ways that are very human but also just a little elevated, humanity at its best; returning to the “episode quality” thing, lows that are very low, but when it’s good, it’s so good that it makes you look at the bad episodes with the same kind of loving forgiveness as when your usually good dog jumps on the counter and eats your leftovers

Moffat-era Doctor Who is a lot like Star Wars: with notable cringy exceptions, largely consistent episode quality; very flashy and often incredibly well done scenery, costumes, ans special effects; grand, epic tone that rarely shifts throughout the series; plots rely on highly charged emotions with a few really clever or deep ideas that may or may not make sense after you think about them a little; mostly about epic heroism in the face of an overarching grand struggle; never quite falls as low as the “bad” episodes of the above, but even at its best has a lot of incredible scenes and moments that aren’t really earned by the characters or the writing but that fans agree to treat as if they are in order to enjoy getting swept up in the spectacle and the drama; fans tend to treat the bad scenes and episodes as a betrayal of the viewing experience they were promised by the franchise rather than the “lol yeah that episode sucked let’s watch it again while drinking and making fun of it” described above
